# Ticket Writing Guide

## When to Activate
- Breaking down a spec document into implementable tickets (po-pm)
- Creating EPIC groupings for medium/large projects
- Mapping dependencies between tickets or EPICs
- Estimating effort for implementation tasks

## Ticket Format (Medium/Large)

```markdown
## [EPIC-{number}] {EPIC title}

### TICKET-{number}: {ticket title}
- **User Story**: As a {role}, I want {feature}, so that {value}
- **Acceptance Criteria**:
  - [ ] Criterion 1
  - [ ] Criterion 2
  - [ ] Error handling: ...
  - [ ] Edge case: ...
- **Estimated Effort**: {0.5h ~ 2h}
- **Dependencies**: TICKET-{number} (or "None")
- **EPIC**: EPIC-{number}
```

## Small Project Ticket Format

Write a flat ticket list without EPIC grouping:

```markdown
### TICKET-{number}: {ticket title}
- **User Story**: As a {role}, I want {feature}, so that {value}
- **Acceptance Criteria**:
  - [ ] Criterion 1
  - [ ] Criterion 2
  - [ ] Error handling: ...
- **Estimated Effort**: {0.5h ~ 2h}
- **Dependencies**: TICKET-{number} (or "None")
```

## EPIC Dependencies (Medium/Large)

Always include an EPIC dependency map when writing tickets:

```markdown
## EPIC Dependency Map
EPIC-01 (Auth) → None
EPIC-02 (Dashboard) → EPIC-01
EPIC-03 (Settings) → EPIC-01, EPIC-02
```

## Guidelines
1. Max 2 hours per ticket for a senior developer — smaller is better
2. User story format is required for every ticket
3. Acceptance criteria must include error handling and edge cases
4. Dependencies must be explicitly recorded
5. Each acceptance criterion becomes one test case (maps to tdd-workflow)

## Integration
- po-pm: Primary author
- test-writer: Consumes tickets to write tests (1:1 mapping)
- tdd-workflow: Each acceptance criterion → one test case
